# CaptionDB Security Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This contract defines the mandatory security standards for the CaptionDB project.

Security is a fundamental engineering requirement.

Every implementation must protect:

- Users
- API Keys
- Uploaded videos
- Generated captions
- System resources
- Infrastructure

Security is not optional.

---

# Security Philosophy

Assume:

Every input is malicious.

Every uploaded file is untrusted.

Every API response could be malformed.

Every network request can fail.

Every external service can become unavailable.

Trust nothing.

Validate everything.

---

# Zero Trust Architecture

Never trust:

User input

Uploaded files

Environment variables

JSON payloads

URLs

HTTP Headers

External APIs

Filesystem paths

Always validate before use.

---

# Secrets Management

Never hardcode:

API Keys

Passwords

Tokens

Secrets

Certificates

Private Keys

Credentials

Secrets must only come from:

Environment Variables

Secret Managers (future)

Encrypted configuration

Never commit secrets to Git.

---

# Logging Rules

Never log:

API Keys

Bearer Tokens

Passwords

Private Prompts

Sensitive Metadata

User Secrets

Personally identifiable information

Logs should be safe to share.

---

# Input Validation

Every request must validate:

Type

Length

Range

Format

Encoding

Required fields

Reject invalid data immediately.

---

# File Upload Security

Validate:

Extension

MIME Type

Magic Bytes

Size

Duration

Resolution

Reject unsupported files.

Never trust filenames.

Generate internal filenames.

---

# Path Traversal Protection

Never concatenate file paths.

Always normalize paths.

Reject:

../

Absolute paths

Invalid characters

Ensure files remain inside approved directories.

---

# Temporary Files

Temporary files must:

Use secure directories

Have unique names

Be cleaned automatically

Never remain after processing

---

# JSON Validation

Validate all JSON.

Reject:

Missing fields

Unknown structures

Invalid types

Malformed payloads

Use Pydantic models whenever possible.

---

# API Security

Validate every request.

Return consistent error messages.

Never expose:

Stack traces

Internal file paths

SQL errors

Framework internals

Third-party exceptions

---

# Authentication

Design APIs to support authentication.

Even if authentication is disabled for the hackathon.

Authentication should remain pluggable.

---

# Authorization

Prepare the architecture for:

User roles

Permissions

Project ownership

Resource isolation

Do not hardcode authorization logic.

---

# Dependency Security

Use pinned dependency versions.

Avoid unmaintained libraries.

Review dependencies before adding.

Remove unused dependencies.

---

# Dependency Scanning

Support automated vulnerability scanning.

Examples:

pip-audit

Safety

Dependabot

GitHub Security

Resolve high severity vulnerabilities before release.

---

# Docker Security

Containers must:

Run as non-root

Use minimal images

Avoid unnecessary packages

Use read-only filesystem where practical

Expose only required ports

Pin base image versions

---

# Network Security

Every HTTP request should define:

Timeout

Retry policy

TLS verification

Connection reuse

Never disable certificate verification.

---

# Fireworks Security

Protect:

API Key

Request payloads

Prompt content

Model configuration

Never expose provider credentials.

---

# Prompt Security

Prompt templates must not contain:

Secrets

Credentials

System information

Internal architecture

Private configuration

Keep prompts isolated from sensitive information.

---

# Output Validation

Validate AI responses before using them.

Reject:

Empty outputs

Malformed structures

Unexpected content

Invalid JSON

Never trust AI output.

---

# Error Handling

Do not expose internal implementation details.

Return safe error messages.

Log detailed information internally.

Users receive friendly responses.

---

# Rate Limiting

Support configurable rate limiting.

Protect:

Upload endpoints

Caption generation

Heavy processing endpoints

Future authentication endpoints

---

# Denial of Service Protection

Reject:

Oversized files

Repeated requests

Malformed payloads

Unexpected content

Protect expensive AI operations.

---

# Resource Limits

Every operation should define:

Maximum file size

Maximum duration

Maximum frame count

Maximum OCR pages

Maximum retries

Maximum memory usage

All limits should be configurable.

---

# CORS

Allow only approved origins.

Never use:

Allow-Origin: *

in production.

Configuration should control allowed origins.

---

# Security Headers

Support:

X-Content-Type-Options

Content-Security-Policy

Referrer-Policy

X-Frame-Options

Strict-Transport-Security (future HTTPS)

---

# Encryption

Support encrypted transport.

Never send secrets over insecure connections.

Prepare for encrypted storage if future persistence is introduced.

---

# Session Security

Future authentication should support:

Secure cookies

Expiration

Refresh

Revocation

Do not hardcode session behavior.

---

# Audit Logging

Record security-relevant events.

Examples:

Authentication failures

Repeated validation failures

Configuration errors

Unexpected provider failures

Do not record sensitive data.

---

# Exception Security

Never leak:

Internal exceptions

Provider exceptions

Database errors

Filesystem structure

Wrap exceptions before returning responses.

---

# Static Analysis

Support:

Bandit

Ruff

MyPy

Security scanning should become part of CI.

---

# Supply Chain Security

Review every dependency.

Prefer official libraries.

Avoid abandoned packages.

Verify package source.

Pin versions.

---

# Secure Defaults

Security features should default to:

Enabled

Users must explicitly disable optional features.

Never default to insecure behavior.

---

# Future Security

Architecture should support:

Authentication

Authorization

Encrypted storage

RBAC

API Gateway

Secrets Manager

Without major redesign.

---

# Security Review Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ No hardcoded secrets

✓ Input validated

✓ Output validated

✓ File uploads protected

✓ Paths sanitized

✓ Exceptions wrapped

✓ Logs sanitized

✓ Dependencies reviewed

✓ Docker secured

✓ Network requests protected

✓ Resource limits enforced

✓ Security headers configured

✓ Tests added

✓ Documentation updated

If any item fails, revise the implementation before completion.

---

End of Security Engineering Contract.
